issue.title: Run a server in bare streams console mode?  ( Trying to setup an Abiotic Factor Server )
issue.body:
I have a VM on a server that I'm trying to run an Abiotic Factor server on.  There isn't even really a GPU.

I've mostly followed directions from these links for dependencies:
https://github.com/DFJacob/AbioticFactorDedicatedServer/issues/3
https://github.com/DFJacob/AbioticFactorDedicatedServer/wiki/Guide-%E2%80%90-Quickstart
Then setup xrdp (and a DE) and umu-run

I suspect the winetricks aren't required but they're part of my present wine environment from earlier tests / attempts.

Currently I installed Linux Steam to the VM and have signed in, but that step might not be necessary; however it seemed to be required to get the game server to proceed past initial startup.

### There's an obvious wine / umu issue.

Umu: The game still runs inside of a new cmd console window, rather than as "bare streams" (stdin/stdout/stderr) ( https://gitlab.winehq.org/wine/wine/-/wikis/Wine-User's-Guide#text-mode-programs-cui-console-user-interface ) on the invoking console. issue.title: fix: handle locals() calls in wrapped modules by static analysis
issue.body:
## Summary

This PR fixes bundling of modules that use `locals()` to dynamically access imported symbols, a pattern used by libraries like httpx to set `__module__` attributes.

## Changes

- **Static analysis for `locals()` calls**: When a module-level `locals()` call is detected, it's replaced with a statically determined dictionary containing all module-level symbols
- **`__all__` reference detection**: Added detection for when `__all__` variable is referenced elsewhere in the module (e.g., in loops), ensuring it's preserved when needed
- **AST builder enhancement**: Added `dict()` and `dict_item()` helper functions to the ast_builder for cleaner dictionary construction
- **Test fixture**: Added test case based on httpx's pattern of using `locals()` to access imported symbols

## Problem & Solution

The issue occurred when bundling modules that use this pattern:
```python
from ._internal import MyClass, my_func
__all__ = ["MyClass", "my_func"]
__locals = locals()  # Capture module-level locals
for __name in __all__:
    setattr(__locals[__name], "__module__", "mypkg")
```

In the bundled wrapper function, `locals()` returns function-local variables, not the imported symbols which are now global. The solution uses static analysis to determine what `locals()` would return at module level and replaces it with a dictionary literal containing the correct symbols.

## Test Results

- ‚úÖ All existing tests pass
- ‚úÖ New test fixture for the httpx pattern works correctly
- ‚úÖ Clippy validation passes (only unused `dict_item` warning, kept for future use)

pull_request.title: feat(map): persist and restore selected map type
pull_request.body:
This introduces functionality to save and automatically restore the user's selected map type (both standard Google Maps types and custom tile provider URLs) across app sessions.

The selected map type is now stored in SharedPreferences. When the MapViewModel is initialized, it attempts to load the previously selected map type.

Specific changes include:
- Added new preference keys `PREF_SELECTED_GOOGLE_MAP_TYPE` and `PREF_SELECTED_CUSTOM_TILE_URL`.
- Implemented `loadPersistedMapType()` to retrieve and apply the saved map type on startup. This function includes logic to validate saved custom URLs and fallback to defaults if a saved type is no longer valid.
- Modified `removeCustomTileProviderConfig` to also clear the custom URL from preferences if it was the selected one.
- Updated `selectCustomTileProvider` to save the selected custom URL to preferences and clear any selected Google Map type.
- Updated `setSelectedGoogleMapType` to save the selected Google Map type to preferences and clear any selected custom URL.
- Ensured that when a custom tile provider is selected, or an invalid one is attempted, the corresponding preference is updated or cleared.
- When loading, if a saved custom URL is no longer in the list of available custom tile providers or is invalid, it is cleared from preferences, and the map defaults to the standard Google Map type.
- Added error handling for loading persisted Google Map types in case the stored name is invalid.

Implements GitHub MCP provider exposing github_get_issue tool with proper error handling, linting compliance, and comprehensive testing. The provider includes token authentication, error classification, and environment variable resolution for secure configuration management.

- Added comprehensive parameter validation and error classification
- Implemented custom token transport for authentication

# üèóÔ∏è Floor Plan to GeoJSON Map Tool

## üìå Project Overview
This project is a web-based tool that allows users to **upload a floor plan image** (e.g., PNG, JPG, or PDF), automatically converts it into **GeoJSON format**, and displays it as an interactive map.  
It can be rendered in **2D or 3D**, similar to mapping tools like MappedIn.

---

## üöÄ Features
- üì§ Upload floor plan images.  
- ü§ñ AI + Computer Vision (OpenCV / AI models) to detect rooms, walls, and pathways.  
- üåç Automatic conversion to **GeoJSON** format.  
- üó∫Ô∏è Interactive map display using **Leaflet.js** (2D) or **Mapbox GL JS** (3D).  
- üíæ Option to export GeoJSON for use in other GIS tools.  
- üîß Extensible design for multi-floor navigation and AR/VR integration.  

---

## üîÑ Workflow
1. User uploads a floor plan image.  
2. Backend processes the image ‚Üí extracts walls/rooms ‚Üí converts to polygons.  
3. GeoJSON file is generated and served to the frontend.  
4. The frontend fetches the GeoJSON and renders it as a navigable map.  

---

- **Backend**: Python (FastAPI / Flask), OpenCV, Shapely, GeoPandas  
- **Frontend**: React, Leaflet.js (2D), Mapbox GL / Three.js (3D)  
- **Storage**: MongoDB (GeoJSON support) or local storage  
- **AI/ML (optional)**: Object detection (YOLO, Segment Anything) for auto room detection
